urll<- "https://query.data.world/s/3frateh23qw5oxlhbalkoy4utc2ghm"

plf <- tempfile()
download.file(urll,plf, mode="wb")
happy_data <- read_excel(path = plf)
view (happy_data)

We are going to look at 5 countries - one from each continent.

UK Canada Peru Uganda India New zealand

NewData <- filter(happy_data, country == "United Kingdom" | country == "Peru" | country == "Canada" | country == "India" | country == "Uganda" | country == "New Zealand")
View(NewData)

Now we are going to run some summary stats One of positive affect for each country

One table looking at life expectancy of each country

Create an animation looking at life expectancy and positive affect in the 5 countries across “year”

my_plot <- NewData %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Positive affect`, y = `Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(x = "Positive affect", y = "Healthy life expenctancy at birth", subtitle = "Year") +
  transition_time(year) + 
  shadow_mark(past = T, future = F, alpha = 0.3) 

animate(my_plot)

my_plot <- NewData %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Positive affect`, y = `Healthy life expectancy at birth`, colour = country)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(x = "Positive affect", y = "Healthy life expenctancy at birth", subtitle = "Year = {closest_state}")  +
  transition_states(year) +
  shadow_mark(past = T, future = F, alpha = 0.3) 

animate(my_plot)

Build a linear model to look at this

can add a regression line to this graph

NewData %>%

  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

we can build a linear model.

model1 <- lm(`Healthy life expectancy at birth`  ~ 1, data = NewData)
model2 <- lm(`Healthy life expectancy at birth` ~ `Positive affect`, data = NewData)

anova(model1, model2)
